Rating: 4
This was time-consuming, but not difficult. The prep work is straightforward and the ingredients are available in your local grocery store. I started too late in the evening ended up having to set my alarm for 3 a.m. to get up and take the beef out of the oven. Start earlier in the day! The flavors are delicious. Overall a great recipe for a low-key night in but elegant and delicious enough for a dinner party. Simply divine!

Rating: 3
To make this dish properly, you should prepare it two days before you plan to serve it. When you let the beef and sauce marry in the fridge, the dish will develope unimaginable levels of flavor. Classic...

Rating: 4
This recipe is cleary a restaurant dish in that the prep work and time required is not the typical for normal "sunday night fare." Being a culinary school refugee I was more than up to the challenge! In the end, it is MORE than worth the time and labor. It is truly wonderful (and I mean like 4 michelin stars at home wonderful). Next time I will likely braise the ribs a day ahead of time, not to save on cooking time, but so I can skim some of the fat out of the sauce. To add to the decadence, I did chocolate souffles for desert, and it was an evening not to be soon forgotten.